}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 112-114.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Large-limbed (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 membruto}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) like Cassius (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXIV.67), Pedro III, king of \softline
Aragon (1276-85), sings along with large-nosed Charles I of Anjou and Provence, king of Naples \softline
and Sicily (1266-85).  Pedro had married Constance, daughter of Manfred (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.115-116), in 1262, a relationship that gave him a claim to the crown of Sicily, which he assumed after \softline
the Sicilian Vespers (1282) and held until his death, despite the efforts of Charles, whom he had \softline
deposed and who died before Pedro, and thus without regaining his crown, in 1285.  Once again \softline
we see enemies united in friendship.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 115-117.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante refers, among Pedro's four sons, either to the firstborn, Alfonso III of \softline
Aragon, who reigned for six years (but not with happy result, according to the chroniclers) after \softline
his father's death (1285-91) and died at twenty-seven, or the last, Pedro, who did indeed die in his \softline
boyhood and was never put on.  However, the text would seem clearly to indicate a son who did \softline
not succeed his father on the throne.  Torraca (comm. to vv. 115-120) makes a strong case for the \softline
unlikelihood of Dante's celebrating Alfonso, thus promoting the candidacy of Pedro (the \softline
'Marcellus' of Aragon, as it were).  He has been followed by most commentators.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 118-120.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Unlike their worthy brother (Pedro?), the other two sons of Pedro III, James \softline
and Frederick, do not possess their father's goodness, but only his territories.  In fact, they went \softline
to war with one another over their claims to power in Sicily, with Frederick eventually winning \softline
out, leaving James to content himself with Aragon.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 121-123.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's sententious moralizing, issuing from the mouth of Sordello, has a \softline
precursor in his earlier words on the same subject in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.xx.5 and IV.xx.7), as \softline
Poletto (comm. to this passage) was perhaps first to point out.  There Dante testified both that \softline
nobility does not descend into an entire family, but into individuals, and that it comes only and \softline
directly from God.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 124-129.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Charles and Pedro, themselves noble of spirit, share the disgrace of degenerate \softline
offspring, the former's son, Charles II, king of Naples and count of Provence (1289-1309), singled \softline
out as being particularly vile.  See Grandgent's explanation (comm. to verse 127) of these lines: \softline
'Charles II is as much inferior to Charles I as Charles I is to Peter [i.e., Pedro] III.  Beatrice of 
Provence and Margaret of Burgundy were the successive wives of Charles I, Constance (daughter \softline
of Manfred) was the wife of Peter; and Charles I was not a devoted husband.  "The plant (the son) \softline
is inferior to the seed (the father) to the same extent that Constance boasts of her husband (Peter) \softline
more than Beatrice and Margaret boast of theirs (Charles)."'  Dante, who has somewhat \softline
surprisingly treated Charles of Anjou with a certain dignity (see the harsh characterizations of him \softline
at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XX.67-69 and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIX.127), now takes some of that away, as Pedro and Charles are \softline
no longer treated with equal respect.  Porena (comm. to vv. 127-129) explains that Dante's \softline
gesture here is meant to show his objectivity; having saved Manfred (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III), he now also saves \softline
Manfred's persecutor, Charles, despite his own political (and moral) disapproval.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 130-132.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Henry III of England (1216-72), disparaged by Sordello in his lament for \softline
